{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"b755a45b-9302-476c-9c5e-bddee7d9c72d","content":"In ASP.NET Core, `AddScoped` creates one instance **per HTTP request** — each request is a natural scope boundary. In MAUI, there's no equivalent of a request. The app has essentially **one long-lived scope** (the application lifetime), so `AddScoped` behaves like `AddSingleton`.\n\nYour DbContext is never disposed/recreated between navigations, so its change tracker accumulates state.\n\n**Fixes:**\n\n1. **Use `AddTransient`** — gives a fresh DbContext each time it's injected.\n2. **Use a DbContext factory:**\n   ```csharp\n   builder.Services.AddDbContextFactory<MyDbContext>();\n   ```\n   Then inject `IDbContextFactory<MyDbContext>` and create short-lived contexts manually:\n   ```csharp\n   using var db = _factory.CreateDbContext();\n   ```\n\nOption 2 is generally preferred — it gives you explicit lifetime control and avoids accidental long-lived contexts holding open connections.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"1888f301-671b-408d-8714-47a1cb60bf41","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a common issue when transitioning from ASP.NET Core to .NET MAUI regarding dependency injection scoping, specifically with `AddScoped` and DbContext lifetime behavior.\n\nThis is a conceptual question I can answer directly without needing to look at any code or files.\n\nThe key issue: In ASP.NET Core, `AddScoped` creates a new instance per HTTP request (each request is a \"scope\"). In MAUI, there's no equivalent of an HTTP request to define scope boundaries — the app has a single long-lived scope (essentially the app lifetime), so `AddScoped` behaves like `AddSingleton`. This means the same DbContext instance is reused across all page navigations, causing data to persist/leak between pages.","outputTokens":416,"requestId":"0820:6A01C:AA9742:C56300:69F2AA4D"},"id":"4c5daab6-2a50-4490-92ba-c1a4d6cfb787","timestamp":"2026-04-30T01:03:20.942Z","parentId":"e1be5141-666d-4e8b-b8d3-1a9b7120bfc4"}
